===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|choppen}}, {{m|enm|chappen|t=to chop}}, of {{unk|en|title=uncertain}} origin. Cognate with {{cog|sco|chap|t=to chop}}. Compare {{cog|stq|kappe}}, {{m|stq|kapje|t=to hack; chop; lop off}}, {{cog|nl|kappen|t=to chop, cut, hew}}, {{cog|nds-de|kappen|t=to cut off; clip}}, {{cog|de|kappen|t=to cut; clip}}, German dialectal {{m|de|chapfen}}, {{m|de|kchapfen|t=to chop into small pieces}}, {{cog|da|kappe|t=to cut, lop off, poll}}, {{cog|sv|kapa|t=to cut}}, {{cog|sq|copë|t=piece, chunk}}, {{cog|ang|*ċippian}} (in {{m|ang|forċippian||to cut off}}). Perhaps related to {{m|en|chip}}.

